# AI analysis contract and validation rules

## Critical principle

Treat all AI/backend meal-analysis output as untrusted external input.

Never assume it is:
- complete
- correctly typed
- numerically valid
- internally consistent
- high confidence
- ready for direct UI rendering or persistence

## Required response discipline

Whenever consuming an analysis response:
- validate schema and nullability
- validate numeric ranges where applicable
- normalize units
- handle missing or partial food items
- handle missing macros
- sanitize labels
- compute totals defensively
- support low-confidence results

Never pass raw external DTOs directly into UI.
Never persist unnormalized external data as if it were canonical domain truth.

## Preferred domain model shape

Unless the repository already defines an approved equivalent, domain concepts should support fields such as:
- analysis id
- meal type
- capture timestamp
- image URI/reference
- analysis status
- foods[]
  - name
  - estimated quantity
  - unit
  - calories
  - protein_g
  - carbs_g
  - fat_g
  - confidence
- total calories
- total protein
- total carbs
- total fat
- overall confidence
- userEdited flag

Do not invent extra nutrition fields unless there is a product or backend requirement.

## Correction-first requirements

The result screen must support correction-first UX.
Users must be able to:
- remove a detected food
- add a missing food
- edit quantity
- edit unit if product allows
- adjust nutrition values if product allows
- save a corrected result

If edits are supported:
- keep AI-estimated values separate from corrected values where useful
- persist corrected values as canonical saved data
- mark the meal as user-corrected

## Error categories to model explicitly

Prefer typed domain/app errors such as:
- network unavailable
- timeout
- upload failed
- invalid server response
- no food detected
- low-confidence analysis
- local save failed
- permission denied
- camera unavailable

Do not swallow parsing or validation failures silently.

## Raw payload handling

If raw AI responses are stored for debugging or auditability:
- store them only if product/security policy allows it
- do not expose them directly to UI
- do not log sensitive data excessively
- avoid storing oversized payloads without clear value

## Future-proofing

Write this layer so it can later support:
- user feedback loops
- corrected meal learning signals
- multiple backend providers/models
- schema evolution

But do not prematurely overengineer these paths if not requested.
